<h2>
    Gear &amp; Techniques
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Bait/Drift rigs:</strong> Corkies, yarnies, roe bounce near seams; 12–20 lb leader, No. 4 to 1/0 hook 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Spinners &amp; Plugs:</strong> Swing spinners/plugs or plunk from bank/seams.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Fly Fishing:</strong> Swing leech patterns (e.g., articulated leeches) on sink-tip lines for seams 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Float Fishing:</strong> Centerpin or Euro rigs are productive in slower stretches.
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Regulations &amp; Conservation
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        Keep only <strong>hatchery-clipped steelhead</strong>; wild fish are protected and must be released 
    </li>
    <li>
        Bait allowed seasonally (North Santiam: Apr 22–Oct 31); artificial-only otherwise 
    </li>
    <li>
        Barbless hooks often required—handle fish gently and minimize air exposure.
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Final Take
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Best all-around go-to:</strong> North Santiam River — numerous access points, reliable summer runs.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Great calm-season wade/drift fishery:</strong> South Santiam — good access and steelhead quality.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Urban convenience:</strong> Willamette in Salem — easy access for float, drift, and bank anglers.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Worth the drive for winter:</strong> Siuslaw River — drift-boat access, strong winter runs.
    </li>
</ul>

